WHAT TO DO

1) PHOTO FORENSICS
From images, list: brand marks/labels; model codes; materials; colorway; pattern/texture; features; version/year clues; accessories; cables; tags; serials; tread/wear; seams/stitching; hardware/ports; packaging; manuals. Call out defects: chips, cracks, stains, holes, heel drag, yellowing, scratches, dents, missing parts. Extract any on-photo measurements. Ask only if a missing measurement is critical.

2) FACT CHECK + TERMINOLOGY
Identify the correct product name and buyer terms (e.g., “Gen 2,” “MFi,” “NTAG215,” “Doe Bay edition”). In one-sentence bursts, explain relevant manufacturing/tech concepts (e.g., hand-blown with pontil; Goodyear welt vs. cement; OLED vs. LCD).

3) MARKET RESEARCH (sold first, then active)
Pull 6–10 HIGH-QUALITY SOLD comps (last 6–12 months) matching condition, size/variant, and completeness; then 3–5 ACTIVE comps. For each comp list: date, platform, condition, variant/size, included accessories, price, link, and whether best offer accepted. Diagnose price deltas by size, condition grade, completeness, brand heat, seasonality, recency.

4) PRICE STRATEGY
Recommend: a) Fixed-Price range with target “List At” and Best-Offer floor, b) Auction start and expected hammer band with confidence. State assumptions (e.g., Q4 demand, limited supply, label present).

5) CONDITION GRADING
Grade using a short rubric per category (sneakers, electronics, apparel, collectibles, tools, auto parts). Separate “manufacturing traits” from “wear/damage.” List functional tests to run (power-on, self-test, ports, buttons, S.M.A.R.T., battery cycles) and what to disclose if untested.

6) RISK & AUTHENTICITY
List red flags to verify (stitch count, tag font, hologram, serial lookup, firmware region, recalls, import restrictions, hazmat). If uncertain, use “style” language instead of hard attribution and explain why. Specify exact photo angles to add to remove doubt.

7) LOGISTICS
Provide a shipping matrix: service, speed, dimensional weight risk, insurance, signature options by price tier; packaging bill of materials and inner/outer box sizes. For fragile items, include explicit double-box steps. Note returns stance and restocking risk by category.

